<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="sermon">
<PB N="39" REF="003029_0041_0FEFAEFF079158F0">
<HEAD>A <HI>Pillar of Salt</HI> to Sea&s;on a corrupt Age.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q><BIBL>LUKE XVII. 32.</BIBL>
<P><HI>Remember</HI> LOT'S <HI>Wife.</HI></P></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>OUR Ble&s;&s;ed SAVIOUR &s;peaking to his Di&s;ciples of the calamitous De&s;truction which &s;hou'd be brought on <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI> warn'd them to flee out of it, when they &s;hou'd &s;ee the <HI>Abomination of De&s;olation &s;tanding in the holy Place: i. e.</HI> The Roman Ar|my be&s;ieging the City. In the ver&s;e immediately pre|ceding our Text he &s;aid, <HI>In that day, he which &s;hall be in the hou&s;e-top, and his &s;taff in the hou&s;e, let him not come down to take it away: and he that is in the field, let him likewi&s;e not turn back:</HI> As if he had &s;aid, Let every one of my Servants make all po&s;&s;i|ble ha&s;te to get out of <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI> when the Judg|ments of GOD &s;hall be irre&s;i&s;tibly breaking in upon it. And to pre&s;s this Advice, and excite them to flee with the greate&s;t &s;peed, He added the&s;e words, <HI>Re|member Lot's Wife.</HI> &mdash; And what he &s;aid to them, he now &s;aith to us all, whom he is warning to flee from Wrath, <HI>Remember Lot's Wife.</HI> We &s;hould remem|ber her, not for our Imitation, but for our Admonition and Awakning. &mdash; We &s;hould remember her Sin, and her Puni&s;hment, and may receive much In&s;truc|tion and &s;piritual Profit therefrom.</P>
<P N="1"><PB N="40" REF="003029_0042_0FEFAF030EDF3870">I. <HI>WE &s;hou'd remember the</HI> SIN <HI>of Lot's Wife.</HI></P>
<P>THIS is recorded, Gen. 19.26. <HI>His Wife looked back from behind him.</HI> In her flight from <HI>Sodom</HI> &s;he looked back. But how was this a Sin? Wherein con&s;i&s;ted the &s;infulne&s;s of her &s;o doing? What fault was it for a poor di&s;tre&s;&s;ed Woman to look back upon the City where &s;he had dwelt, and where her Friends &amp; Acquaintance were, and from whence &s;he was taking her final Departure? Might &s;he not without offence turn her Eyes upon <HI>Sodom</HI> as &s;he was e&s;caping from it? Might &s;he not &s;ee it once more before it was utterly con&s;umed? Might &s;he not ca&s;t an Eye of Pity towards, and Weep for her mi&s;erable Neighbours in flames of Brim&s;tone?</P>
<P>HER looking back was &s;inful,</P>
<P N="1">1. BECAUSE it was contrary to a <HI>divine Prohibition.</HI></P>
<P><HI>SIN is a Tran&s;gre&s;&s;ion of the Law. Lot's</HI> Wive's looking back on <HI>Sodom</HI> was the Tran&s;gre&s;&s;ion of a particular Law, the breach of an expre&s;s Order given them, Gen. 19.17. <HI>It came to pa&s;s when they had brought them forth abroad, that he &s;aid, E&s;cape for thy Life, look not behind thee. Lot</HI>'s Wife, as well as he, was &s;olemnly Charged not to <HI>look behind;</HI> &s;o that &s;he did that which was expre&s;ly and plainly forbidden her. And to act contrary to the lea&s;t Commandment, or Prohibition of the great GOD, is no &s;mall offence, no petty fault. <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wive's Di&s;o|bedience may be illu&s;trated by that of <HI>Saul</HI>'s, in &s;pa|ring the be&s;t of the <HI>Amalekites</HI> Sheep and Oxen for Sacrifice; This was very offen&s;ive to GOD, becau&s;e contrary to an expre&s;s Order given him to &s;lay them all: The Prophet thus &s;et his Sin before him, 1 Sam. 15, 22, 23. <HI>Hath the Lord as great delight in burnt-offerings and &s;acrifices, as in obeying the voice of the Lord? Behold, to obey is better than &s;acrifice, and to hearken than the fat of Rams. For rebellion is as the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word"> of witchcraft, and &s;tubbornne&s;s it is as iniquity and idolatry. Saul</HI>'s rebellion in that matter, which was in it &s;elf &s;mall, was as really a Sin, &amp; Provocation
<PB N="41" REF="003029_0043_0FEFAF04A9D96100">
of GOD'S Wrath as Witchcraft or Idolatry. It was a Contempt of the great Lawgiver's Authority. And &s;o was <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wive's looking back. <HI>Abraham</HI> the &s;ame Morning looked toward <HI>Sodom,</HI> and &s;aw the &s;moke of it's Torments a&s;cending, <HI>Gen.</HI> 19.27, 28. This was no Sin in <HI>Abraham,</HI> for he was not for|bidden to look toward <HI>Sodom:</HI> But it was a great Sin in <HI>Lot's Wife</HI> to look back upon it, for the Lord had &s;aid to her, <HI>Look not behind thee.</HI></P>
<P>THIS teacheth us, to mea&s;ure Sin by the Command|ment; and &s;o it will appear <HI>exceeding &s;inful.</HI> Per&s;ons are ready to make light of many evil Actions, and to &s;troke them with a gentle Cen&s;ure, becau&s;e they are not &s;o gro&s;s &amp; crying as others. But the matter in which we Sin is not &s;o much to be regarded, as the Authority which is thereby de&s;pi&s;ed. What is in it &s;elf &s;mall &amp; incon&s;i|derable is a great offence, if the Lord hath forbidden it. The fir&s;t Woman took of the fruit of a certain Tree in <HI>Eden,</HI> and eat it. Could &s;o &s;mall a thing as the eat|ing an Apple be very offen&s;ive to GOD? Yet <HI>the Lord God &s;aid unto the Woman, What is this thou ha&s;t done?</HI> Gen. 3.13. What an heinous Crime ha&s;t thou committed? Becau&s;e GOD had expre&s;ly &s;aid, <HI>Of that Tree thou &s;halt not eat.</HI> GOD'S Authority is con|temned, his Will re&s;i&s;ted by our doing the lea&s;t thing which he hath forbidden; therefore no &s;uch Act mu&s;t be accounted by us a &s;mall offence. We &s;hould not &s;ay of it, as <HI>Lot</HI> did of <HI>Zoar,</HI> which he de&s;ir'd might be &s;pared to be the City of his Refuge, <HI>Is it not a little One?</HI> Sometimes the &s;maller the matter is in which we tran&s;gre&s;s, the greater is the Offence; as when the Prohibition of it is very plain &amp; peremp|tory, the Temptation unto it &s;light, and it be a thing which might ea&s;ily be left undone. What&s;oever we do contrary to the declared Will of GOD, is a horrid In|dignity offer'd to his Maje&s;ty &amp; Authority: It is Re|bellion, which in every ca&s;e is as the Sin of Witchcraft and Idolatry.</P>
<P N="2">2. IN <HI>Lot's Wive's</HI> looking back upon <HI>Sodom</HI> there was a <HI>Contempt of GOD's Omni&s;cience.</HI></P>
<P>SHE not only de&s;pis'd the Authority &amp; Com|mandment
<PB N="42" REF="003029_0044_0FEFAF07E1BAA4C0">
of GOD, but al&s;o practically deny'd his Omni&s;cience: for it is &s;aid, that &s;he <HI>locked back from behind Lot.</HI> She committed this Sin &s;ecretly. She was behind her Husband; and &s;ince his Eye was not upon her, &s;he ventur'd to look back; thereby expre&s;|&s;ing a Contempt of GOD'S all-&s;eeing Eye. She was afraid that if <HI>righteous Lot</HI> &s;aw her he wou'd be angry with her for di&s;obeying the Lord; but not afraid that a <HI>Righteous GOD</HI> would &s;ee her, and be di&s;plea|&s;ed at her Sin. This is an aggravation of &s;ecret Sins, that the Omni&s;cience of GOD is e&s;pecially contemned thereby; as if the Eye of GOD was not to be &s;o much regarded &amp; reverenc'd as the Eye of Man.</P>
<P N="3">3. <HI>LOT</HI>'s <HI>Wive's</HI> looking back on <HI>Sodom</HI> procee|ded from an <HI>evil Heart of Unbelief.</HI></P>
<P>THE <HI>Angels</HI> which came to <HI>Lot</HI>'s Hou&s;e, told him, and his Wife, that &s;wift De&s;truction was coming upon <HI>Sodom: Lot</HI> inform'd his Sons in-law of it, and &s;aid unto them, <HI>Up, get ye out of this place, for the Lord will de&s;troy this city: but he &s;eemed unto them as one that mocked.</HI> Altho' his <HI>Wife</HI> did not reject the Warning with &s;uch &s;corn, as they did, yet it &s;eems, that &s;he que&s;tion'd the Truth of the Threatning, and therefore look'd back to &s;ee whether it would be Executed or not. It was &s;aid to her, <HI>Look not behind thee, le&s;t thou be con&s;umed.</HI> But &s;he did not believe &s;he &s;hou'd be con&s;umed for looking back. It is &s;aid in the Book of the <HI>Wi&s;dom of Solomon,</HI> chap. 10. v. 7. <HI>That a &s;tanding Pillar of Salt, is a Monument of an unbelieving Soul.</HI>&mdash;Not to believe GOD, is to make him a Liar: It is a great Sin, to doubt of his Veracity in his Menaces, as well as Promi&s;es. Such Unbelief is the Root of Di&s;obedience. Men de&s;pi&s;e the Com|mandments of GOD, becau&s;e they do not believe his Threatnings, Heb. 3.12. <HI>Take heed, Brethren, le&s;t there be in any of you an evil heart of unbelief, in de|parting from the living God.</HI></P>
<P N="4">4. THERE was the <HI>Lu&s;t of the Eye</HI> in <HI>Lot's Wive's</HI> looking back upon <HI>Sodom.</HI></P>
<P>"IT was a look of Covetou&s;ne&s;s". <HI>Sodom</HI> was a rich and plea&s;ant place: It was even <HI>as the Garden of
<PB N="43" REF="003029_0045_0FEFAF09F4D227E0">
the Lord,</HI> Gen. 13.10. <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife was very loth to go out of it; &s;he lingered in it, (as indeed <HI>Lot</HI> him&s;elf did) after &s;he was warned to flee; the An|gels laid hold on her hand, and brought her forth, and &s;et her without the City, <HI>plucking her as a Brand out of the Fire:</HI> and &s;he went not far from <HI>Sodom</HI> before her Love to her worldly accommodations there, made her look back, with unea&s;y De&s;ires to return to it, there to enjoy the Wealth, Plea&s;ures &amp; Friends which &s;he had left. So that her Sin was great: her Rebellion was as the Sin of Idolatry, for <HI>Covetou&s;ne&s;s is Idolatry:</HI> It is loving and &s;erving the Crea|ture more than the Creator. We cannot obey GOD, &s;o long as this Lu&s;t remains unmortified: We may &s;eem to hearken to his Call for a time, and to flee from Wrath; but if we love the World, and the things of it, we &s;hall look, and draw back unto Perdition, 2 Tim. 4.10. <HI>Demas hath for&s;aken me, having lo|ved this pre&s;ent World.</HI> We &s;hould remember <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, that we may <HI>take heed and beware of Cove|tou&s;ne&s;s.</HI></P>
<P N="5">5. <HI>LOT</HI>'s Wive's looking back on <HI>Sodom</HI> imply'd a <HI>Contempt of the Mercy of GOD</HI> in delivering her out of it.</P>
<P>WHEN the <HI>Lord</HI> was about to rain "Hell out of Heaven" upon <HI>Sodom,</HI> and the Neighbouring Cities, he &s;ent his Angels (and one of them was the ble&s;&s;ed Angel of the Covenant, for he is &s;tiled <HI>Jehovah,</HI> Gen. 19.24.) GOD &s;ent them to bring out <HI>Lot,</HI> and his Wife and Children, that they might not be con&s;umed in the Iniquity &amp; Overthrow of <HI>Sodom.</HI> The <HI>Lord</HI> being <HI>merciful</HI> did this: <HI>Lot</HI> &s;pake of it with Admiration, &s;ay|ing, <HI>Behold now, thy Servant hath found Grace in thy &s;ight, and thou ha&s;t magnified thy mercy which thou ha&s;t &s;hewed unto me in &s;aving my Life.</HI> But his Wife de&s;pi&s;ed &s;o great a Mercy; &s;he had low Thot's of it: &s;he did not accept the miraculous Deliverance with Thankfulne&s;s: &s;he was &s;o un&s;uitably affected with the Kindne&s;s GOD had &s;hown her in &s;aving her Life, that &s;he look'd back on <HI>Sodom</HI> with a di&s;contented Eye, be|cau&s;e &s;he was <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word"> from her worldly Enjoyments there.
<PB N="44" REF="003029_0046_0FEFAF0D4EB70B48">
This vile Ingratitude made her Sin &s;o heinous in GOD'S &s;ight. When Mercy is de&s;pi&s;ed, Wrath is ex|a&s;perated: Sins committed after &s;ignal Deliverances, are exceedingly aggravated. Ezra 9.13, 14.&mdash; <HI>Seeing that thou our God ha&s;t given us &s;uch Deliverance as this, &s;hould we again break thy Commandments?</HI> The gracious GOD hath &s;ent the chief of tho&s;e Angels which he &s;ent to <HI>Sodom,</HI> the glorious increated Angel, the <HI>Lord Je&s;us Chri&s;t</HI> into the World, to deliver us from the everla&s;ting Burnings of Hell: Let us not imi|tate <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife in de&s;pi&s;ing this great Mercy.</P>
<P>THUS we &s;hould remember and improve the <HI>Sin</HI> of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife.</P>
<P N="2">II. <HI>WE &s;hou'd remember the</HI> PUNISHMENT <HI>of</HI> Lot's <HI>Wife:</HI> the terrible Judgment which GOD inflicted upon her.</P>
<P>THIS is recorded for our Admonition, Gen. 19.26. <HI>She became a Pillar of Salt.</HI> When &s;he looked back, &s;he was &s;truck dead upon the &s;pot, and was turned into a <HI>Pillar of Salt.</HI> By her becoming a Pillar of Salt, &s;ome I think, under&s;tand no more than her being made a la&s;ting Monument of GOD'S &s;evere Ju&s;tice; as a perpe|tual Covenant is &s;tiled a <HI>Covenant of Salt,</HI> Num. 18.19. But why the literal Sen&s;e of the words &s;hould be rejec|ted, I can &s;ee no Rea&s;on; but do believe that &s;he was really turned into a <HI>Pillar,</HI> a Statue <HI>of Salt,</HI> a kind of rocky, mineral Salt, which will endure all Weathers and not wa&s;te away. <HI>Naturali&s;ts</HI> write of Salt which is hard enough for Buildings.&mdash; <HI>Jo&s;ephus,</HI> who lived &s;ince <HI>Chri&s;t</HI> was on Earth, &s;aith that the Pillar of Salt was &s;tanding in his Time, and that He him&s;elf had &s;een it. And the like is affirmed by others &s;ince his time. &mdash; We are now call'd to look upon it with the Eyes of our Minds.</P>
<P N="1">1. WE &s;hou'd remember the Puni&s;hment of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, becau&s;e it repre&s;ents to us the <HI>evil Nature,</HI> and <HI>infinite Demerit</HI> of Sin.</P>
<P><HI>LOT</HI>'s Wives Puni&s;hment was &s;evere &amp; dreadful, yet it did not exceed the de&s;ert of her Crime, for look|ing back upon <HI>Sodom,</HI> &s;he was turned into a <HI>Pillar of Salt.</HI>&mdash;By this we may learn, That there is more Evil
<PB N="45" REF="003029_0047_0FEFAF106F400220">
in every Sin, than Men are aware of: It is more di&s;|plea&s;ing to the <HI>holy GOD</HI> than we can imagine it to be: GOD'S Thot's of Sin are not as Man's; his ac|count of it and Man's are very different. The Infi|nite Being again&s;t whom Sin is committed, and who only knows the Malignity &amp; Demerit of it, does not make light of the &s;malle&s;t Sin. <HI>The Wages of</HI> every <HI>Sin is Death.</HI> And the righteous GOD, to &s;hew his Hatred of Sin, and what a heavy Puni&s;hment it de|&s;erves, &s;ometimes in this World remarkably executes Vengeance upon Men, for tho&s;e Faults, which to a common Eye appear &s;mall &amp; incon&s;iderable. He that turned <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife into a Pillar of Salt, for looking back on <HI>Sodom,</HI> &s;truck <HI>Uzzah</HI> dead, for touching the Ark; and &s;mote the Men of <HI>Beth&s;heme&s;h</HI> Fifty Thou|&s;and, three&s;core and ten, for looking into it. <HI>Behold therefore the &s;everity of God: on them which fell &s;everity,</HI> Rom. 11.22.&mdash; Jer. 2.19. <HI>Know therefore and &s;ee, that it is an evil thing and bitter, that thou ha&s;t for&s;aken the Lord thy God, and that my fear is not in thee, &s;aith the Lord God of ho&s;ts.</HI>&mdash; On the <HI>Pillar of Salt</HI> is engraven the De&s;ert &amp; Doom of every Sinner among&s;t us, and <HI>He that runs may read it. Lot</HI>'s Wife is thus &s;et forth for an Example, &s;hewing to us what we de&s;erve for our Rebellion, Athei&s;m, Unbelief, Covetou&s;ne&s;s, and Contempt of GOD'S Mercy. Was <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife a greater Sinner than You, or I? They are not always the greate&s;t offenders, on whom GOD inflicts the mo&s;t vi&s;ible Judgments in this World, See <HI>Luk.</HI> 13.1, 2, 3, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> We &s;hou'd look upon the Pillar of Salt, that our Fle&s;h may tremble for fear of GOD, and that we may be afraid of his Judg|ments. The De&s;ert of Sin is &s;till the &s;ame, and GOD is immutably and impartially Ju&s;t; what he hath done to others, he may do to us. It is certain, that unle&s;s our Repentance prevent, GOD'S Wrath will fall upon us, if not in &s;uch a manner, yet as terribly as it did upon <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife: and as it will be more tolerable for <HI>Sodom</HI> &amp; <HI>Gomorrah,</HI> &s;o it will for <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife in the Day of Judgment, than for us, if we continue to neg|lect &amp; de&s;pi&s;e the great Mercy of GOD in &s;ending his
<PB N="46" REF="003029_0048_0FEFAF1201DF85D0">
Angel, the Lord JESUS, to deliver us from the Lake that burns with Fire &amp; Brim&s;tone.</P>
<P N="2">2. WE &s;hou'd remember the Puni&s;hment of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, and be convinced of the <HI>Folly and Danger of &s;inning in Secret.</HI></P>
<P>SHE looked back from behind <HI>Lot,</HI> &s;o that he could not ob&s;erve and reprove her; but &s;he was before GOD, did that Evil in His &s;ight, and He rebuk'd her in His Anger. GOD'S Judgments will &s;ooner or later find Men out in their mo&s;t &s;ecret Sins, Zeph. 1.12. <HI>I will &s;earch Jeru&s;alem with candles, and puni&s;h the men that are &s;ettled on their lees; that &s;ay in their heart, the Lord will not do good, neither will he do evil.</HI> There is no darkne&s;s, nor &s;hadow of Death, in which the workers of Iniquity can hide them&s;elves from his Eyes, which are as a flame of Fire. If we are Religious &amp; Pray in Secret, our gracious Father in Hea|ven will reward us openly: But if we are Wicked, and Sin in Secret, our righteous Judge will puni&s;h us openly; if not in this World, yet &s;adly in that which is to come. Wo unto their Soul, who declare their Sin as <HI>Sodom,</HI> and hide it not: Wo al&s;o unto theirs, who conceal their Sin as <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, for GOD will reveal it, and reckon with them for it.</P>
<P N="3">3. WE &s;hou'd remember <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wive's Puni&s;hment, and not de&s;ire, nor delight in the <HI>forbidden Society of vicious Per&s;ons, le&s;t we be involved in their Ruin.</HI></P>
<P><HI>LOT</HI>'s Wife lingered in, and look'd back upon <HI>Sodom,</HI> wi&s;hing (mo&s;t probably) that &s;he might en|joy the Company of her Friends &amp; Acquaintance there; and therefore &s;he &s;uffer'd with them. GOD's exemplary Vengeance was poured down on her at the &s;ame time, that it was on them; and it is probable in the &s;ame manner. Fire &amp; Brim&s;tone might be rained on her, as well as on them. A judicious Divine thus expounds that Text, Gen. 19.24. <HI>The Lord rained upon Sodom and upon Gomorrah, brim&s;tone &amp; fire;</HI> that is, He con&s;umed them by Thunder &amp; Lightning. Which (&s;aith he) &s;ome of the Pagans had notice of, for <HI>Taci|tus</HI> tells us, that tho&s;e Cities were &s;et on fire and burnt up by the &s;troke of Thunder. <HI>He adds,</HI> The
<PB N="47" REF="003029_0049_0FEFAF163392E180">
Saline Pillar which <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife was turned into, was probably the Effect of this wonderful Meteor; for from &s;everal Examples it appears, that Per&s;ons &s;truck with Thunder have continued in the &s;ame Po&s;ture wherein they were when they were alive, and their dead Bodies are &s;tiffned by the &s;ulphurious Va|pours penetrating them. But whether <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife was &s;truck dead with a fla&s;h of that Fire which burned <HI>Sodom</HI> or not, yet &s;he was de&s;troyed with that wicked People; and as <HI>Sodom</HI> was turned into a Lake, Heaps and Pits of Salt <NOTE N="&Verbar;" PLACE="foot"><HI>Gen.</HI> 14.3. <HI>Deut</HI> 29.23. <HI>Zeph.</HI> 2.9.</NOTE>, &s;o <HI>Lot</HI>'s, Wife was turned into a <HI>Pillar of Salt.</HI> She partook of the &s;ame Cur&s;e. This is a Warning to us, not to hanker after the forbidden Society of lewd &amp; wicked Per&s;ons, le&s;t we be de&s;troyed with them. If we have fellow&s;hip with the unfruitful Works of Darkne&s;s, we &s;hall be led forth with the Workers of Iniquity. If our Life be now among the Unclean, we may expect &s;oon to have our part with them in the Lake which burneth with Fire &amp; Brim|&s;tone, Rev. 18.4. <HI>I heard another voice from Heaven, &s;aying, Come out of her, my People, that ye be not partakers of her &s;ins, and that ye receive not of her plagues.</HI></P>
<P N="4">4. WE &s;hou'd remember the Puni&s;hment of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, that &s;udden De&s;truction from <HI>GOD</HI> may be a <HI>Terror</HI> to us.</P>
<P>WHEN <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife looked back, &s;he immediately became a <HI>Pillar of Salt:</HI> She was &s;truck dead in a moment. This in&s;tance of GOD'S Wrath &s;hou'd make us &s;en&s;ible how obnoxious we are to &s;udden De&s;tructi|on. The Long-&s;uffering of GOD waited upon <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, while &s;he lingred in <HI>Sodom;</HI> but when &s;he looked back, his Wrath made quick work. GOD hath exer|cis'd great Patience toward us, yet he may bring &s;wift De&s;truction upon us, I&s;a. 42.13, 14. <HI>The Lord &s;hall go forth as a mighty man, he &s;hall &s;tir up jealou&s;y like a man of war: he &s;hall cry, yea, roar; he &s;hall pre|vail again&s;t his Enemies. I have a long time held my peace, I have been &s;till &amp; refrained my &s;elf, now will
<PB N="48" REF="003029_0050_0FEFAF18C1C34B40">
I cry like a travailing woman, I will de&s;troy and devour at once.</HI> While we are in our Sins, we have no Security, no, not for one moment, from the de&s;troy|ing Judgments of GOD. Vengeance which hath been hitherto delayed, may overtake and &s;urprize us in the next Act of Sin. If we proceed a &s;tep further in an evil Cour&s;e, our feet may &s;tumble, and we fall head-long into Perdition. We &s;hou'd remember <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, and other Examples of &s;udden De&s;truction, and <HI>&s;tand on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word">, and nor &s;in.</HI> Let Unclean Per&s;ons remember <HI>Zimri</HI> &amp; <HI>Cozbi,</HI> on whom vengeance was executed in the very Act of their Uncleanne&s;s, <HI>Numb.</HI> 25.8. When any one is tempted to that wickedne&s;s, let him think of the Dart that &s;triketh thro' the Liver, <HI>Prov.</HI> 7.23. Let proud &amp; arrogant Sinners remember <HI>Herod, whom the Angel of the Lord &s;mote immediately,</HI> Acts 12.23. Let Riotous &amp; Profane Per&s;ons remember <HI>Bel&s;hazzar,</HI> who was &s;lain in that Night, when his Heart was merry with Wine, and no Ve&s;&s;els but tho&s;e of the <HI>Sanctuary</HI> wou'd &s;erve him for a drunken Fro|lick, Dan. 5. &mdash; Luk. 21.34. <HI>Take heed to your &s;elves, le&s;t at any time your hearts be over-charged with &s;urfeiting and drunkenne&s;s, and the cares of this Life, and &s;o that day come upon you unawares.</HI> Let all carele&s;s, &s;en&s;ual and worldly Wretches remember the Sinners of the old World, and of <HI>Sodom,</HI> who gave up them&s;elves wholly to their &s;ecular Bu&s;ine&s;s and car+nal Delights, till the Flood and the fiery Storm came and de&s;troyed them all. Let us not put the evil Day far from us. "The Prophet gives us the Alarm like one that awakens a Family with the cry of <HI>Fire, Fire,</HI>" Zeph. 1.14. <HI>The great day of the Lord is near, it is near, and ha&s;teth greatly.</HI> Peals of Warning are now &s;ounded in our Ears both from the Word and the Pro|vidence of GOD, and if our &s;tupid Hearts are not moved with fear, and we do not flee from Wrath, we may look for &s;udden &amp; inevitable De&s;truction, Prov. 29.1. <HI>He that being often reproved, hardneth his neck, &s;hall &s;uddenly be de&s;troyed, and that without re|medy.</HI></P>
<P N="5"><PB N="49" REF="003029_0051_0FEFAF1BE0B5C398">5. WE &s;hou'd remember the Judgment inflicted on <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, and fear le&s;t we bring on our &s;elves a <HI>&s;trange Puni&s;hment.</HI></P>
<P>THIS was a &s;trange Puni&s;hment, a Woman turned into a <HI>Pillar of Salt.</HI> Not only the &s;uddenne&s;s, but al&s;o the &s;trangene&s;s of a Puni&s;hment is to be dreaded. The common Calamities of Mankind are apt to be look'd upon by too many, as the Effects of natural Cau&s;es only, or to be a&s;crib'd to <HI>Fortune:</HI> GOD there|fore &s;ometimes goes out of the beaten Road of his Ju|dicial Di&s;pen&s;ations, and inflicts &s;ome rare, extraordi|nary Judgment, to awaken the drow&s;y World to take notice of his Hand. Numb. 16.29, 30, 31. <HI>If the&s;e men die the common death of all men, or if they be vi&s;ited after the vi&s;itation of all men, then the Lord hath not &s;ent me. But if the Lord make a new thing, and the Earth open her mouth, and &s;wallow them up, with all that appertain unto them, and they go down quick into the Pit: then ye &s;hall under&s;tand that the&s;e men have provoked the Lord. And it came to pa&s;s as he had made an end of &s;peaking all the&s;e words, that the ground clave a&s;under that was under them: and the Earth opened her mouth &amp; &s;wallowed them up.</HI> We &s;hould fear and tremble, le&s;t GOD &s;hould vi&s;it us with &s;ome &s;uch unu&s;ual Judgment, Job 31.3. <HI>Is not de&s;truction to the wicked? and a &s;trange puni&s;h|ment to the workers of iniquity?</HI> De&s;truction will certainly be their Portion, unle&s;s they Repent, and it may be brought upon them in &s;ome extraordinary and dreadful manner, I&s;a. 28.21. <HI>The Lord &s;hall ri&s;e up as in mount Perazim, he &s;hall be wroth as in the val|ley of Gibeon, that he may do his work, his &s;trange work; and bring to pa&s;s his act his &s;trange act.</HI></P>
<P N="6">6. WE &s;hou'd remember the Puni&s;hment of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, and be <HI>deterred from Sin</HI> by the <HI>Shame</HI> which is the Fruit of it.</P>
<P>IT was a <HI>di&s;graceful</HI> Puni&s;hment that <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife &s;uffered. The Pillar of Salt into which &s;he was turned was a la&s;ting Memorial of her Sin &amp; Folly, and perpe|tuates her Shame. Men always di&s;honour GOD by &s;inning again&s;t him; and &s;ometimes in puni&s;hing of
<PB N="50" REF="003029_0052_0FEFAF1D69773818">
them in this World he &s;ets a mark of peculiar Infamy upon them, and cau&s;eth their Sins to be remembred to their Di&s;grace in after-Ages. His Judgments in|flicted upon them are <HI>monumental Pillars,</HI> on which their Sins are written to their great reproach and perpetual &s;hame. Some Puni&s;hments are like <HI>Pillars of Salt,</HI> not to keep Sinners Names from &s;tinking in the no&s;trils of Po&s;terity, but to pre&s;erve the Memory of them to their everla&s;ting Di&s;grace. In &s;ome Exe|cutions of divine Ju&s;tice, GOD doth, as it were hang up Malefactors in Chains, and make them "Specta|cles of public Shame". Ezek. 5.14, 15. <HI>I will make thee a reproach among the Nations that are round about thee, in the &s;ight of all that pa&s;s by. So it &s;hall be a reproach and a taunt, an in&s;truction and an a&s;toni&s;hment unto the Nations that are round about thee, when I &s;hall execute Judgments in thee in anger, and in fury, and in furious rebukes.</HI></P>
<P>THUS in the Judgment inflicted on <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, there is much In&s;truction &amp; Warning given unto us. It may therefore be very profitable for us to remember her <HI>Puni&s;hment.</HI></P>
<P>HAVING &s;poken thus di&s;tinctly, <HI>fir&s;t,</HI> Of the Sin, and <HI>&s;econdly,</HI> Of the Puni&s;hment of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, and &s;hown how we &s;hould remember &amp; improve each of them,&mdash; I would under a <HI>third</HI> general Head,</P>
<P N="3">III. CONSIDER them TOGETHER, and &s;how what the In&s;truction &amp; Warning is, which they <HI>jointly</HI> afford us: and it is this, viz. <HI>That in our flight from</HI> my&s;tical Sodom, <HI>we &s;hould not look back.</HI></P>
<P>THIS is the chief &amp; comprehen&s;ive Benefit de&s;ign'd us by the great Lover of our Souls, in calling upon us to <HI>remember Lot's Wife,</HI> namely, That we might be deter'd from looking back, when we are flying from Wrath. CHRIST &s;aid to his Di&s;ciples, <HI>In that Day</HI> (meaning the day of GOD'S vengeance again&s;t <HI>Jeru&s;a|lem) let not him that is in the field turn back. Re|member Lot's Wife. As if he had &s;aid,</HI> You mu&s;t
<PB N="51" REF="003029_0053_0FEFAF1EF7AC9040">
flee out of <HI>Jeru&s;alem</HI> with all po&s;&s;ible &s;peed, and beware le&s;t you imitate <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife, who as &s;he was e&s;caping from <HI>Sodom</HI> looked back upon it, and for &s;o doing was immediately turned into a <HI>Pillar of Salt.</HI> And what CHRIST &s;aid to them is applicable, and is now directed to us all in this &s;olemn <HI>Memento</HI> and Caution,</P>
<P><HI>REMEMBER</HI> Lot's <HI>Wife, and in your flight from</HI> &s;piritual Sodom <HI>take heed that ye look not back, le&s;t ye al&s;o be Con&s;umed.</HI></P>
<P>THAT this Admonition may be &s;et in a clear Light before our Under&s;tandings, and come with power on our Hearts and Con&s;ciences, and have a good Influ|ence into our Behaviour, I wou'd ob&s;erve to you,</P>
<P N="1">I. <HI>THAT while Men are in the Corrupt</HI> State of Nature, <HI>they are my&s;tically in</HI> Sodom.</P>
<P>THEY are in &s;uch a Condition as <HI>Sodom</HI> was an Emblem of. They are &s;o both in re&s;pect of the gro&s;s Pollution which they are wallowing in, and the dread|ful De&s;truction which they are expo&s;ed to. <HI>Sodom</HI> was a very polluted and dangerous Place; the State of Na|ture is &s;uch a State: All that are in it, are in as deep Pollution and great Danger, as tho&s;e who dwelt in <HI>Sodom.</HI> &mdash; Let this two-fold Re&s;emblance betwixt <HI>Sodom</HI> and a State of Nature be con&s;ider'd by us,</P>
<P N="1">1. UNCONVERTED Sinners may be fitly &s;aid to be in <HI>Sodom,</HI> in regard of that <HI>Pollution</HI> which they wallow in</P>
<P><HI>SODOM</HI> was a <HI>Sink</HI> of moral Pollution, in which the People like Swine did wallow: and &s;o it repre|&s;ented the Corrupt State of Nature, in which the Children of Men are altogether filthy.</P>
<P>IT is &s;aid, Gen. 13.13. That <HI>the Men of</HI> Sodom <HI>were wicked, and &s;inners before the Lord exceedingly.</HI> And this may be truly &s;aid of all that are in the State of Nature: Tho' they are not all in re&s;pect of actual Sins, &s;o wicked as the Men of <HI>Sodom</HI> were, yet they are in re&s;pect of the habitual <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word"> and Perver&s;ene&s;s of their Nature. Original Sin is greater than all the
<PB N="52" REF="003029_0054_0FEFAF2227AB3660">
actual Abominations that were committed in <HI>Sodom. Sodom</HI> was a <HI>Sink,</HI> but corrupt Nature is a <HI>Foun|tain</HI> of moral Defilements: And there is more filthy Water in this Fountain, than ever i&s;&s;ued forth in the impure &s;treams of <HI>Sodom.</HI> The Fountain did not ca&s;t out all it's dirty Waters, even in that &s;o defiled Land. Altho' that People did <HI>draw iniquity with cords of vanity and &s;in as it were with a rope,</HI> yet they did not draw the Fountain dry. But as the Streams di&s;cover what the Fountain is, &s;o the abomi|nable Wickedne&s;s in <HI>Sodom,</HI> &s;heweth to us what the Corruption of our fallen Nature is. And tho&s;e who are in the State of Polluted Nature, are in re&s;pect thereof more filthy &amp; de&s;perately wicked, than the People of <HI>Sodom,</HI> were in re&s;pect of the actual Abominations which prevailed in it. They dwell amid&s;t greater Impurities, than tho&s;e which were vi&s;ible, and did openly abound in <HI>Sodom.</HI></P>
<P>THERE is this remarkable difference between <HI>Sodom</HI> and a State of Nature; It was po&s;&s;ible for a Man to be Righteous in the former, but it is not &s;o in the latter. Indeed, there were not ten righteous Per&s;ons to be found in <HI>Sodom,</HI> when the LORD came down to &s;ee whether the People had done altogether according to the Cry that went up to him; yet there was One good Man that lived in it at that time; <HI>Ju&s;t Lot, vexed,</HI> and &s;o not corrupted, <HI>with the filthy conver&s;ation of the wicked there: For that righteous man dwelling among them, in &s;eeing and hearing, vexed his righte|ous &s;oul from day to day with their unlawful deeds,</HI> 2 Pet. 2.7, 8. It was po&s;&s;ible, tho' very difficult for one to live in <HI>Sodom,</HI> and not be infected with the Sins of that Place; but it is impo&s;&s;ible for one to abide in the State of Nature, and to be free from the Pol|lutions of it, Job 15.14. <HI>What is man that he &s;hould be clean? and he which is born of a woman, that he &s;hould be righteous?</HI> It is impo&s;&s;ible for him to be &s;o, till he is born of GOD, and there be a Change of his Heart and State.</P>
<P>IT is true, that many who remain in their natural Condition, do appear righteous in the eye of the World;
<PB N="53" REF="003029_0055_0FEFAF2558D617E0">
but they are not &s;o in the &s;ight of GOD: They may be outwardly clean; may wa&s;h the out-&s;ide of the Cup and Platter, and garni&s;h the Sepulchre with &s;pe|cious &s;hews of Devotion; but are inwardly defiled, full of all Uncleanne&s;s, &s;piritual Putrefaction, Hypo|cri&s;y and Iniquity, Luke 16.15. <HI>He &s;aid unto them, Ye are they which ju&s;tifie your &s;elves before men; but God knoweth your hearts: for that which is highly e&s;teemed among&s;t men, is abomintion in the &s;ight of God.</HI> Further, As all unconverted Sinners are, in re&s;pect of the Pollution of their Nature, in &s;piritual <HI>Sodom,</HI> &s;o many of them may be fitly &s;aid to be &s;o, in regard of the actual Defilements which they wal|low in. The Soil of corrupt Nature yieldeth the Fruits of <HI>Sodom,</HI> Deut. 32.32. <HI>Their vine is of the vine of</HI> Sodom, <HI>and of the fields of</HI> Gomorrah: <HI>their grapes are grapes of gall, their clu&s;ters are bitter.</HI> Such are addre&s;&s;ed as Inhabitants of <HI>Sodom</HI> &amp; <HI>Gomor|rah,</HI> who practis'd the Sins which abounded there, I&s;a. 1.10. <HI>Hear the word of the Lord, ye rulers of</HI> Sodom; <HI>give ear unto the law of our God, ye peo|ple of</HI> Gomorrah. The Rulers and People of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> had made them&s;elves in re&s;pect of Sin, like tho&s;e of <HI>Sodom</HI> and <HI>Gomorrah,</HI> therefore the faithful Prophet gave them this Title: They de&s;erved no better. <HI>Rome</HI> is called <HI>Sodom</HI> for it's re&s;embling it in Whordom, and all filthine&s;s both of Fle&s;h and Spirit, Rev. 11.8. <HI>Their dead bodies &s;hall lie in the &s;treet of the great <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word">, which &s;piritually is called</HI> Sodom. What Multitudes are there who live in the Practice of the abominable Sins of <HI>Sodom,</HI> Pride, fulne&s;s of Bread, (<HI>i. e.</HI> Exce&s;s in Meats and Drinks,) abundance of Idlene&s;s, Uncharitablene&s;s and Oppre&s;&s;ion? How many, like the People of <HI>Sodom,</HI> give them&s;elves over unto Laciviou&s;ne&s;s, to work all Uncleanne&s;s with greedine&s;s? How many declare their Sin as <HI>Sodom,</HI> and hide it not? Their Foreheads are &s;teel'd with Impudence, they boa&s;t of their Wickedne&s;s, and glory in their Shame. How wretchedly &s;ecure are the mo&s;t in the State of Nature, as the People were in <HI>Sodom?</HI> They are &s;etled on their filthy Lees, quiet &amp; undi&s;turb'd
<PB N="54" REF="003029_0056_0FEFAF26F3176050">
in their Sins, giving them&s;elves up wholly to &s;ecular Bu&s;ine&s;s, and &s;en&s;ual Delights. <HI>As it was in the days of Lot; they did eat, they drank, they bought, they &s;old, they planted, they builded,</HI> not fearing De&s;tructi|on till it was brought upon them: <HI>Even &s;o it is al&s;o in the days of the Son of Man.</HI></P>
<P>THUS in re&s;pect of original Corruption, and actual Abominations, Sinners, wherever they dwell on the face of the Earth, are the people of <HI>Sodom.</HI> In a &s;piritual &s;en&s;e they live in <HI>Sodom.</HI> GOD may ju&s;tly &s;ay concerning all who are in the State of polluted Na|ture, as in Jer. 23.14. <HI>They are all of them unto me as</HI> Sodom, <HI>and the Inhabitants thereof as</HI> Gomorrah.</P>
<P N="2">2. ALL unconverted Sinners may be fitly &s;aid to be in <HI>Sodom,</HI> in re&s;pect of that <HI>De&s;truction</HI> to which, they are expos'd.</P>
<P>THE State of Nature is like <HI>Sodom,</HI> not only in re|gard of the <HI>Pollution</HI> but al&s;o of the <HI>Puni&s;hment</HI> of tho&s;e who continue in it. GOD'S exemplary Venge|ance on <HI>Sodom</HI> is mentioned in our Context, ver. 29. <HI>The &s;ame day that</HI> Lot <HI>went out of</HI> Sodom, <HI>it rained fire and brim&s;tone from Heaven, and de&s;troyed them all.</HI> Agreable to the Account given of it, Gen. 19. 24, 25. <HI>The Lord rained upon</HI> Sodom <HI>and upon</HI> Go|morrah, <HI>brim&s;tone and fire from the Lord out of Hea|ven. And he overthrew tho&s;e cities, and all the plain, and all the inhabitants of the cities.</HI> Now this was Emblematical of the utter De&s;truction of all tho&s;e who finally remain in the State of Nature; &s;o the Scriptures inform us, 2 Pet. 2.6. <HI>Turning the cities of</HI> Sodom <HI>and</HI> Gomorrah <HI>into a&s;hes, condemned them with an overthrow, making them an en&s;ample unto tho&s;e that after &s;hould live ungodly.</HI> The Ruin of the People of <HI>Sodom</HI> &s;heweth to all who live ungodly, what they mu&s;t expect, and what their End will cer|tainly be, if they remain in a State of Nature, <HI>viz. to be burned.</HI> The Fire which con&s;umed the Inhabitants of Sodom, was a Type of Hell-fire, which &s;hall con&s;ume all the Adver&s;aries of GOD, Jude v. 7. <HI>Even as</HI> Sodom <HI>and</HI> Gomorrah, <HI>and the cities about them in like man|ner
<PB N="55" REF="003029_0057_0FEFAF2A8E3ABEF8">
giving them&s;elves over to fornication, and going after &s;trange fle&s;h are &s;et forth as an example, &s;uffer|ing the vengeance of eternal fire.</HI> The Fire which de&s;troyed them is &s;aid to be <HI>Eternal,</HI> either becau&s;e of the &s;till continuing Effects of it, or rather, becau&s;e it was a Type or Repre&s;entation of the Fire of Hell, and to tho&s;e mi&s;erable Sodomites the very beginning of it, they being brought by tho&s;e temporal Flames into everla&s;ting Burnings <NOTE N="&dagger;" PLACE="foot"><HI>Pool</HI>'s Annot.</NOTE>. The terrible De&s;truction of the Sinners in <HI>Sodom,</HI> by Fire and Brim&s;tone, was a lively Repre&s;entation of the &s;ad and eternal Ruin of all impenitent Sinners. <HI>Upon the wicked God &s;hall rain &s;nares, fire and brim&s;tone, and an horrible tem|pe&s;t: this &s;hall be the portion 'of their cup. The Heavens and the Earth which are now, by the &s;ame Word</HI> which created them, <HI>are kept in &s;tore, re&s;er|ved unto fire, again&s;t the day of Judgment, and perdition of ungodly men. &mdash; Then &s;hall the King, the righteous Judge, &s;ay unto them on the left hand, Depart from me, ye Cur&s;ed, into everla&s;ting fire. And they &s;hall be ca&s;t into a lake of fire, burning with brim&s;tone.</HI> Thus, as the Inhabitants of Sodom were all de&s;troyed by Fire and Brim&s;tone, &s;o the Scriptures &s;peak of the final De&s;truction of all impe|nitent Sinners, as that which &s;hall be by Fire &amp; Brim|&s;tone, whether properly or metaphorically, I &s;hall not di&s;pute: But only &s;ay, that if we take the&s;e Scrip|tures in a figurative &s;en&s;e, they repre&s;ent the Pains of the Damned to be at lea&s;t as exqui&s;ite &amp; intolerable, as tho&s;e which Fire and Brim&s;tone can produce. How did the poor tormented Wretches in <HI>Sodom</HI> run &s;cream|ing about, when &s;howers of flaming Brim&s;tone came down upon them, and their Bodies were &s;o many blazing Torches! Alas, How then will mi&s;erable Sinners roar out, gna&s;h their Teeth, and gnaw their Tongues for Pain and Angui&s;h, when they &s;hall be thrown into the Lake that burns with Fire and Brim|&s;tone, which is the &s;econd Death, far wor&s;e than the fir&s;t! &mdash; Now let Sinners in Zion (who are al&s;o
<PB N="56" REF="003029_0058_0FEFAF2D02983710">
in &s;piritual Sodom) be afraid, let <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word"> take hold on Hypocrites; for who among <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hall dwell with the devouring Fire? Who among&s;t us &s;hall dwell with everla&s;ting Burnings?</P>
<P>THUS we &s;ee in what re&s;pects the State of Nature may be &s;piritually called <HI>Sodom.</HI></P>
<P>Ob&s;. II. <HI>THAT the Children of Men are warned to</HI> Flee <HI>out of &s;piritual</HI> Sodom.</P>
<P><HI>LOT's</HI> Wife, and others in <HI>Sodom,</HI> were fore-warned of the burning Tempe&s;t which GOD would rain upon it, and were compa&s;&s;ionately advis'd &amp; urg'd to get out of <HI>Sodom,</HI> that they might not be involv'd in it's overthrow. GOD &s;ent Angels from Heaven, to give them notice of the approaching Ruin: yea, the <HI>Me&s;&s;enger of the Covenant</HI> was &s;ent on this Errand. Tho&s;e Mini&s;ters of GOD called upon <HI>Lot,</HI> his Wife and Daughters, to make ha&s;te, and get out of the accur&s;ed City; And while they lingered in <HI>Sodom,</HI> being; loth to leave their commodious Dwelling, rich E&s;tate, and worldly Conveniencies, the Angels laid hold on their hands, and brought them forth, and &s;et them without the City and charged them to e&s;cape for their Lives, and not to &s;tay in all the Plain, but to e&s;cape to the Mountain, <HI>Gen.</HI> 19. In like manner the gracious GOD deals with the Children of Men, who are in <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom. He warns them to get out of the polluted, dangerous E&s;tate of Nature: He &s;ends his Mini&s;ters, the <HI>Angels of the Churches,</HI> who cry aloud, and &s;hew unto Sinners their Danger, Duty and In|tere&s;t; calling earne&s;tly upon them to for&s;ake their Sins, and part with all which is incon&s;i&s;tent with the Safety and Salvation of their Souls: yea, the glorious increated Angel doth by the Mini&s;try of the Word come, and warn Sinners to e&s;cape out of <HI>my&s;tical Sodom.</HI> 2 Cor. 5.20. <HI>Now then we are Amba&s;&s;a|dors for Chri&s;t, as though God did be&s;eech you by us: we pray you in Chri&s;t's &s;tead, Be ye reconciled to God&punc;</HI>&mdash; By awakning Di&s;pen&s;ations of his <HI>Providence,</HI> and &s;trong Convictions of his Spirit, the LORD doth, as it were, lay hold on the hands of lingring Sinners,
<PB N="57" REF="003029_0059_0FEFAF2F4BC8B558">
and pull them out of <HI>Sodom;</HI> making them leave off the practice of their gro&s;s Abominations, and to u&s;e &s;ome Endeavours to reform their Lives, and &s;ave their Soul.&mdash; Thus graciou&s;ly is the Long-&s;uffering GOD pleas'd to warn tho&s;e who are in <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom, to ha&s;ten out of it, and flee to the City of Refuge, which he hath appointed and prepared for them, le&s;t they be con&s;umed with his fiery Indignation, which he will pour out on all who remain in the corrupt and ac|cur&s;ed State of Nature. Matth. 3.7. <HI>O Generation of vipers, who hath <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="1 word"> you to flee from the wrath to come?</HI>&mdash; When the GOD of Ho&s;ts is coming forth in his Judgments again&s;t his Enemies, he ob&s;erves that Law of Arms which he gave the I&s;raelites; which was, to offer Terms of Peace to a City before they a&s;&s;aulted it, Deut. 20.10. <HI>When thou come&s;t nigh unto a city to fight again&s;t it, then proclaim peace unto it.</HI> So the LORD, who is a <HI>Man of War,</HI> &s;ounds a Parly with the Trumpet of his Word, and monitory Pro|vidences, before he di&s;chargeth the Cannons of his de|&s;troying Judgments: He Summons his Enemies to a Treaty of Peace, <HI>[Prepare to meet thy God O I&s;rael]</HI> before he falls on them with the Artillery of his Ven|geance. He gives Notice to Sinners of their approach|ing Ruin, that &s;o by their Repentance they might prevent it, Jer. 18.11. <HI>Thus &s;aith the Lord, Behold, I frame evil again&s;t you, and devi&s;e a device again&s;t you: return ye now every one from his evil way, and make your ways, and your doings good &mdash; Hear now the word of the Lord, ye men of</HI> Sodom; <HI>Give ear, Ye people of</HI> Gomorrah, all that are in the pollu|ted dangerous E&s;tate of Nature: &mdash; <HI>Wa&s;h ye, make you clean, put away the evil of your doings from before mine eyes, cea&s;e to do evil, learn to do well&mdash; Come now and let us rea&s;on together, &s;aith the Lord: Tho' your &s;ins be as &s;carlet, they &s;hall be as white as &s;now; tho' they be red like crim&s;on, they &s;hall be as wool. If ye be willing and obedient, ye &s;hall eat the good of the land: But if ye refu&s;e and rebel, ye &s;hall be devoured &mdash; O Earth, Earth, Earth, hear the word of the Lord:</HI> O <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="UOM" EXTENT="4 letters">le&s;s, &s;tupid Sinners,
<PB N="58" REF="003029_0060_0FEFAF30DE82A758">
who mind earthly things, ye are again and again warned and intreated, to get out of <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom, le&s;t Fire and Brim&s;tone be rained upon you. Zech. 2.6. <HI>Ho, ho, come forth, and flee from the land of the North, &s;aith the Lord.</HI> Ye are now earne&s;tly called upon, to come forth, and flee from the Land of the South, as well as from the Land of the North &mdash; from my&s;tical <HI>Sodom,</HI> as well as <HI>Babylon.</HI> Will you &s;till linger, when the Clouds of GOD'S Di&s;plea&s;ure are vi&s;ibly hanging over our Heads, ready to bur&s;t with Thunder and Lightning; and the Earth under us is &s;en&s;ibly heaving to vomit out Fire and Brim|&s;tone, to con&s;ume us? O Sinners, make ha&s;te, delay no longer to get out of the State of Nature, and to keep GOD'S Commandments.&mdash;E&s;cape for your Lives, &mdash; the Lives of your precious Souls.&mdash; E&s;cape to the Mountain, the Mountain of the LORD'S Hou&s;e:&mdash; Flee to CHRIST for Refuge.&mdash; Flee as Men pur&s;ued with the greate&s;t Danger.&mdash; Flee with all po&s;&s;ible &s;peed &mdash; Yea, <HI>Flee like as they fled from before the Earthquake, in the days of</HI> Uzziah <HI>King of Judah.</HI></P>
<P>LET me not &s;eem to any of you, as <HI>Lot</HI> did to his <HI>Sons in Law,</HI> even <HI>as one that mocked.</HI></P>
<P>Ob&s;. III. <HI>THAT in their flight from &s;piritual</HI> Sodom, <HI>Per&s;ons are apt to</HI> look back.</P>
<P><HI>LOT's</HI> Wife was brought without the City, and &s;he fled with him and her Daughters a while toward <HI>Zoar,</HI> and was in a fair way to e&s;cape the Ruin, which was then coming on the People of <HI>Sodom;</HI> But &s;he &s;lacken'd her Pace, linger'd behind, and looked back. This Sin of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife is imitated by many in their flight from <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom: They are &s;o far awaken'd and wro't upon, that they abandon their vicious Practices, and &s;eem to be brought out of the State of polluted Nature; they turn their backs upon <HI>Sodom,</HI> and &s;et their faces towards <HI>Zion,</HI> and are in a fair way to e&s;cape the wrath of GOD: they run well for a time; take con&s;iderable Pains in Religion, &s;trive to enter in at the &s;trait Gate of Repentance &amp; Faith, labour to get
<PB N="59" REF="003029_0061_0FEF96F8714BDB98">
into CHRIST: perform holy Duties with much &s;eriou&s;|ne&s;s, and apply them&s;elves to the Work of their Sal|vation with fear and trembling; and they are <HI>not far from the Kingdom of GOD:</HI> But they do not <HI>hold on,</HI> their Heat is &s;oon &s;pent, and they flag: Their dread of GOD'S Wrath, and concern for their Souls abate; good Impre&s;&s;ions wear off; and they meeting with Difficulties in the way of Salvation, grow weary of the Chri&s;tian Race, &s;tand &s;till, and <HI>look back</HI> &mdash;. They are tempted to think, there is no need of &s;o much Care about their Souls, that they were in no &s;uch Danger as they apprehended them to be; that the Fire &amp; Brim&s;tone which they were told of, and affrighted with, will not be rained upon them: The Love of the World and the things of it, revives in them; and they fancy it was never better with them, than when they were quiet and undi&s;turb'd in the Enjoyment of their outward Comforts, and &s;en&s;ual Delights; and &s;o thro' Unbelief, and Love of this World, they (as <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife did) <HI>look back</HI> with De|&s;ires of returning to their former Plea&s;ures. The State of &s;piritual Pollution and Bondage appears not &s;o bad to them, as when they were fir&s;t awaken'd to get out of it; nay, better than that of Holine&s;s, which they have been &s;triving to get into: As the <HI>I&s;raelites,</HI> in their Journey to <HI>Canaan,</HI> thought that it was better with them in <HI>Egypt,</HI> and <HI>&s;aid one to another; let us make us a captain, and let us return into Egypt,</HI> Numb. 14.4. &mdash; They who &s;eem to have e&s;caped out of <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom, and to have made con&s;iderable Progre&s;s toward <HI>Zion,</HI> do not ordinarily go back at once, but by degrees. They fir&s;t <HI>look back;</HI> they grow weary of Prayer, and other Duties, are le&s;s fre|quent and fervent therein: <HI>They &s;ay, Behold, what a wearine&s;s is it? and they bring the torn, the lame and &s;ick for an offering to the Lord;</HI> Their Minds hanker after their former Company and Delights: Temptations increa&s;e upon them daily, and they are more and more inclin'd to re&s;ume their abandon'd Lu&s;ts, and to renew their fellow&s;hip with the unfruitful Works of darkne&s;s. Having thus <HI>looked back,</HI> they
<PB N="60" REF="003029_0062_0FEFAF3663E3CE20">
commonly (unle&s;s prevented by &s;udden De&s;truction) go back to <HI>Sodom;</HI> revert to their old Abominations. Prov. 26.11. <HI>As a Dog returneth to his vomit, &s;o a Fool returneth to his folly.</HI> This is cited by the <HI>Apo&s;tle,</HI> and apply'd to the Apo&s;tates in his time, [O that it were not verified in many of us!] 2 Pet. 2.22. <HI>It is happened unto them according to the true Proverb, The Dog is turned to his own vomit, and the Sow that was wa&s;hed to her wallowing in the mire.</HI></P>
<P>Ob&s;. IV. <HI>AWAKNED Sinners, in their flight from &s;piritual</HI> Sodom, <HI>&s;hould</HI> remember Lot's Wife, <HI>that &s;o they may be deter'd from</HI> looking back.</P>
<P>PERSONS may imitate the Sin, and incur the Puni&s;h|ment of <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife, tho' they do not attempt an E&s;cape out of my&s;tical <HI>Sodom:</HI> may be guilty of Di&s;obedience, Contempt of GOD'S All-&s;eeing Eye, of Unbelief, Covetou&s;ne&s;s and Ingratitude for the Mercy of GOD in offering to &s;ave them from the flames of Hell; and thereby may expo&s;e them&s;elves to &s;udden and &s;hame|ful De&s;truction: But &s;uch as have begun their flight from <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom, (as I hope, &s;ome here pre&s;ent have,) if they look back, they e&s;pecially do imitate <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wives Sin, and may expect as terrible a Puni&s;h|ment as Her's: It is therefore peculiarly &s;ea&s;onable, and may be very profitable for tho&s;e who are endea|vouring to get out of <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom, are &s;ollicitou&s;ly <HI>asking the way to Zion, with their faces thitherwards,</HI> and are flying from Wrath to come, to <HI>remember Lot's Wife. Look not behind</HI> you, le&s;t ye be con&s;umed&mdash; Will it not be as great a Sin in you, to <HI>look back,</HI> as it was in <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife? And may you not well be afraid of as great a Judgment, as that inflicted on her? If you <HI>look back,</HI> ye may become <HI>Pillars of Salt,</HI> Mo|numents of GOD'S &s;evere Ju&s;tice, Spectacles of Shame and everla&s;ting Reproach. If GOD doth not immedi|ately con&s;ume you, he may righteou&s;ly &s;mite you with Judicial Hardne&s;s; &s;eal you up to Ruin by final Ob|duration, letting you &s;tand a few Years more in this World, only as occa&s;ions to glorify his Power &amp; Wrath
<PB N="61" REF="003029_0063_0FEFAF3AD906E7F8">
upon you in the next. <HI>Theophilact</HI> &s;aith, <HI>Lot</HI>'s Wife remain'd ob&s;tinate and impenitent, and her Heatt was hardned, and that this is the meaning of her being turned into a Pillar of Salt: Altho' his Interpretation of the Text is not to be embrac'd, yet it may be im|prov'd by tho&s;e who are in their flight from <HI>&s;piritual</HI> Sodom, to deter them from looking back, le&s;t in his &s;en&s;e they become Pillars of hardned Salt.</P>
<P>Zeph. 1.6. <HI>I will &s;tretch out my hand, and cut off them that are turned back.</HI> In the days of <HI>Jo&s;iah,</HI> wherein this Threatning was denounced, the &s;inful People of <HI>Judah</HI> were greatly awaken'd, &amp; outwardly Reformed: But they &s;oon revolted: Many that began well, &s;et out with Zeal in the good ways of the Lord, <HI>turned and looked back:</HI> GOD threatned them parti|cularly, that he would &s;tretch out his hand, and cut them off, wou'd be quick and &s;evere upon them. &mdash; Remember the words of CHRIST, Luk. 9.62. <HI>No man having put his hand to the plough, and looking back, is fit for the Kingdom of God.</HI> Go through with the work that ye have begun, or ye &s;hall never enter into the <HI>Kingdom of God.</HI> Oh! Con&s;ider the Dan|ger and Mi&s;chief of <HI>looking back.</HI> If ye return to your former Abominations, the unclean Spirit will have a &s;tronger Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of you, than he had before, Matth. 12.43, 44, 45. <HI>When the unclean Spirit is gone out of a man, he walketh thro' dry places, &s;eeking re&s;t, and findeth none. Then he &s;aith, I will return into my hou&s;e from whence I came out, and when he is come, he findeth it empty, &s;wept, and garni&s;hed. Then goeth he, and taketh with him&s;elf &s;even other Spirits more wicked than him&s;elf, and they enter in and dwell there: and the la&s;t State of that man is wor&s;e than the fir&s;t.</HI> This is well Expounded by the Apo&s;tle, 2 Pet. 2.20, 21. <HI>For if after they have e&s;caped the pollutions of the world, thro' the knowledge of the Lord and Saviour Je&s;us Chri&s;t, they are again in|tangled therein, and overcome; the latter end is wor&s;e with them than the beginning. For it had been bet|ter for them not to have known the way of Righteou&s;|ne&s;s,
<PB N="62" REF="003029_0064_0FEFAF3E9640AF90">
than after they have known it, to turn from the holy Commandment delivered unto them.</HI></P>
<P>IF ye &s;hould be intangled again in your Lu&s;ts, and return to the Mire of your Sinful Pollutions, your E&s;cape, if ever it be attempted by you, will be far more difficult than it was at fir&s;t; your Deliverance out of Spiritual <HI>Sodom,</HI> will be almo&s;t de&s;paired of.&mdash; Ye having begun in the Spirit, be not &s;o fooli&s;h as to end in the fle&s;h. &mdash; If any of you have &s;lacken'd your pace, and are turning and drawing back, be convinc'd of your folly and danger, and quickned in your flight to CHRIST, by what ye now hear, &mdash; Gal. 5.7. <HI>Ye did run well, who did hinder you, that you &s;hould not obey the truth?</HI> &mdash; Renew your Re&s;olutions again&s;t Sin, and for Holine&s;s and Heaven: Lay a&s;ide every weight, and the Sin that doth &s;o ea&s;ily be&s;et you, and run with patience and per&s;eve|rence the Race &s;et before you: &mdash; and as ye run, <HI>Remember Lot's Wife.</HI></P>
<P><HI>IN fine,</HI></P>
<P>LET &s;uch as are really brought forth out of &s;piri|tual <HI>Sodom,</HI> and <HI>have fled for Refuge to lay hold on the Hope &s;et before them, Remember Lot's Wife,</HI> to deter them al&s;o from looking back. Indeed, tho&s;e who are e&s;caped out of my&s;tical <HI>Sodom,</HI> ought to look back thereon, with an admiring Eye at the infinite Mercy of GOD, in plucking them as <HI>Brands out of the Fire.</HI> They &s;hou'd reflect on their former polluted and mi&s;erable E&s;tate, to excite their Thank|fulne&s;s unto GOD for delivering them out of it; laying hold on their hearts by his omnipotent Grace, when they lingred in &s;piritual <HI>Sodom,</HI> and effectually bringing them out of it. There is a looking back, which may &s;erve to aba&s;e them, and exalt divine Grace, I&s;ai. 51.1. <HI>Hearken to me, ye that follow af|ter Righteou&s;ne&s;s, ye that &s;eek the Lord: look unto the Rock whence ye are hewen, and to the hole of the pit whence ye are digged.</HI> But they mu&s;t not
<PB N="63" REF="003029_0065_0FEFAF40AD2A60C0">
look back on &s;piritual Sodom with any Regret for their leaving it, nor de&s;ire of returning to it. &mdash; They are not, it's true, of <HI>them who draw back unto Per|dition,</HI> Heb. 10.39. GOD'S electing Love, Cove|nant-faithfulne&s;s, almighty Power, and CHRIST'S continual Interce&s;&s;ion &s;hall prevent the total Defection of the Saints. But they are prone to look back, and to go back al&s;o a con&s;iderable way toward <HI>Sodom.</HI> Declen&s;ions are very common among the &s;incere People of GOD. They frequently &s;lacken their Pace in the good ways of the LORD; grow Cold in Re|ligion, remi&s;s in holy Duties, do abate much of their Zeal for GOD, and back-&s;lide into many Sins. Altho' they &s;hall not draw back unto eternal Perdition; yet they may to their &s;piritual Lo&s;s, and temporal De|&s;truction: They may provoke GOD to inflict &s;uch Judgments on them, as to make them Monuments of his righteous di&s;plea&s;ure again&s;t the Sin of <HI>looking back.</HI> Dr. <HI>Edwards</HI> &s;aith, <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Theol. ref. v. <HI>1.</HI> p. <HI>257.</HI></NOTE> That it is not improba|ble that <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife, who was turn'd into a Pillar of Salt, was &s;aved notwith&s;tanding this Judgment &s;ent upon her by GOD. We have (&s;aith he) no ill Cha|racter of this Woman in the Scripture: [he might as truly have &s;aid, that we have no good one:] we cannot (&s;aith he) gather from any thing that is &s;aid in the &s;acred Hi&s;tory that &s;he had been a wicked Per|&s;on: [neither can we that &s;he had been a righteous Per&s;on:] But this we know, &s;aith he, that &s;he was the Con&s;ort of a pious Saint, and beloved of GOD: [we al&s;o know that a wicked Woman is &s;ometimes the Wife of a godly Man:] And we know, &s;aith he, that &s;he was mercifully deliver'd out of <HI>Sodom,</HI> as well as her Husband: [&s;o might <HI>Lot's</HI> Sons in Law have been, had they not laugh'd at the warning gi|ven them.] Tho' I perceive not the &s;trength of tho&s;e Rea&s;ons which the <HI>Doctor</HI> gives, why it is not improbable that <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife was a good Woman, yet I am di&s;pos'd to be of the mo&s;t Charitable Opinion, if there are as probable Grounds to &s;upport it as the
<PB N="64" REF="003029_0066_0FEFAF4279B1AF10">
contrary. And if &s;he was a good Woman, the Pun|i&s;hment inflicted on her may the more deter the Saints from looking back: for it &s;heweth how the Jealous GOD re&s;ents this Sin in his own Children.&mdash; Let them remember <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife, and not imitate her Sin, but <HI>Paul's</HI> Example; Phil. 3.13, 14. <HI>Brethren, I count not my &s;elf to have apprehended, but this one thing I do, forgetting tho&s;e things which are behind, and reaching forth unto tho&s;e things which are be|fore; I pre&s;s toward the mark, for the Prize of the high calling of God in Chri&s;t Je&s;us.</HI> &mdash; Let them remember <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife, that &s;o they may re&s;i&s;t and vanqui&s;h all Temptations to Apo&s;tacy: and if they do &s;o, they &s;hall become glorious <HI>Pillars</HI> in the hea|venly Temple, bearing the mo&s;t honourable In&s;crip|tion; Rev. 3.12, 13. <HI>Him that overcometh, will I make a Pillar in the Temple of my God, and he &s;hall go no more out: and I will write upon him the Name of my God, and the Name of the City of my God, which is new Jeru&s;alem, which cometh down out of Heaven from my God; and I will write upon him my new Name.</HI></P>
<P>HE THAT HATH AN EAR, LET HIM HEAR WHAT THE SPIRIT SAITH UNTO THE CHURCHES.</P>
<P>THUS I thought it meet to &s;tir you up, by putting you in Remembrance of <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife. And if you are Careful to improve what hath been &s;aid, You &s;hall find that <HI>that Pillar of Salt</HI> hath not to this day lo&s;t it's Savour; but that your Hearts are &s;ea&s;oned thereby with &s;uch Caution, and holy fear, as will be of un|&s;peakable &amp; eternal Advantage to you: Wherefore, Be not forgetful Hearers, but Remember <HI>Lot's</HI> Wife.</P>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
